<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Commons Select Committee on the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs inquiry into Food Security</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Scientific Alliance</span></h2><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Food security </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has two components: production</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and availability. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Global harvests have increased very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significantly since the 1960s and ‘70s, when Paul Ehrlich’s prediction of Malthusian catastrophe was in vogue. The global population has probably never been as well fed as now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with a nominal sufficiency of food available and even the effects of regional h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arvest failures being largely offset by the benefits of international trade. Nevertheless, although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he proportion of the population which is chronically undernourished has continued to fall, the absolute number remains stubbornly high, at not much less th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an one billion. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is a problem of availability; people either cannot afford to buy food or the infrastructure is insufficient to deliver it to them. For the purpose of this submission, we will deal only with the issue of production, covering availabilit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y only insofar as consumption in the UK and EU reduces food security elsewhere.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Food security is, fortunately, not a big issue for the EU or EU given the ability to import freely. However, we cannot be complacent, particularly as we have to recognise that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decisions we make about our own food supply may have an impact elsewhere in the world. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One issue which is raised on occasions is that of ‘land grabs’, where productive land in some developing countries is used to grow food for export rather than domestic c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsumption. This is not in itself necessarily a problem, since export earnings will contribute to the health of the l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal economy. And even if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> developing countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increase their agricultural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> productivity significantly, to the extent that they might</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sidered self-sufficient, this is no guarantee that food will be equitably distributed. A key case in point is India, which has improved yields enormously but still is home to about 30% of the world’s chronically malnourished. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK farming, though highly pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ductive, has high fixed costs and is uncompetitive with some other major producers for a range of commodities. This is particularly true for protein crops, upon which much of the livestock industry depends. Importing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">soy and maize as a basis for animal fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d helps to keep the prices of meat, milk and eggs reasonable. Other farming produce can be sourced either domestically or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> abroad, with seasonality playing a big part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the pattern. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although a completely free market approach to farming might make eco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nomic sense at one level, we have to remember that we use farmers to manage landscapes as well as provide food. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Subsidies – which in any case are increasingly decoupled from production – reward farmers for the environmental services they provide as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> encouraging more production than might otherwise be justified. In a world which will require continued increases in food production, maintaining the existing productive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> farmland makes sense in terms of contributing to future global needs. The current high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> comparative costs for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">European agriculture may not be the same in future decades and it is therefore important to maintain an efficient agricultural sector to provide for future needs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite a strong ‘organic’ food lobby and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continued opposition to ge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">netically modified crops from a small but vocal core of activists, it seems that UK and other European consumers are more concerned about food price and quality than the technology used to produce it (see, for example, a recent review of literature on cons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">umer attitudes</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite the romanticisation of the countryside and the perception of farming as traditional, agriculture has always been subject to change, with many farmers always being ready to try some new way of improving yields or reducing costs. G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enetic modification is simply one further technology – albeit an important and powerful one – which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gives the potential for further improvement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">GM technology allows seed companies to introduce specific traits without unwanted changes to the genetic backgr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ound of elite crop varieties. However, despite its potential and flexibility, the cost and complexity of compliance with a highly stringent regulatory system means that taking new products to m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arket largely remains the preserve of the major international s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eed companies. Even these companies will only use genetic modification when the desired variety cannot be produced through any of the other technologies currently falling under the heading of ‘conventional’ breeding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To date, GM crops nearly all have eith</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er or both of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">two important agronomic traits: herbicide tolerance or pest resistance. These are valuable to farmers and have given the technology an increasing year-on-year share of the seed market since they were first commercialised in the mid-1990s. Ins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ect resistant (Bt) maize has been grown every year in northern Spain since before the effective moratorium on new approvals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. While this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> particular crop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be of limited use in the UK, herbicide tolerance would be a boon to many farmers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These crops are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> identical to ‘conventional’ varieties except for the specific GM trait and therefore go into commodity grain streams. While there is no direct consume</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r benefit, the ability to produce reliable harvests and reduce costs contributes to overall lower grain, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oil and animal feed prices. The crops therefore make a real contribution to food security.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Looking further ahead, genetic modification has the potential to deliver varieties which are stress tolerant (able to resist drought and/or flooding) and which eithe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r use fertilizers more efficiently or – in the longer term – actually are able to fix nitrogen in a similar way to legumes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such traits could produce real benefits for European farmers but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also deliver hope of better and more consistent harvests to develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing world farmers. The contribution to global food security would be very significant. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While supporting the availability of GM crops for farmers to choose to grow as they wish, we recognise that modern biotechnology is not a panacea and that there is also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> plenty of scope for innovation through the application of other scientific knowledge. Precision farming, for example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">already makes a real contribution to resource efficiency for some farmers and there are many more opportunities for these gains to be ext</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ended, perhaps via use of autonomous robotic devices. GM technology is an important tool, and its power to deliver is enhanced by integration with other complementary technologies. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Farmers are always vulnerable to the vagaries of the weather and whatever climatic changes may occur </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may increase some problems but will not change the basic picture. Cold or cloudy growing seasons will hold back growth, delay maturation and reduce harvest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s. 2012 was the wettest summer in the UK for a century and had a significant effect on harvests but only a limited impact on the availability and price of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">particular crops. Similarly, unusually hot and dry summers such as in 1976 place harvests in jeopardy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unless sufficient irrigation can be given. Storms can ruin crops even if growing conditions have otherwise been excellent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Under these circumstances, established regional and global supply chains have been robust enough to ensure security of the food supp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly, and seem able to cope with such major disruptions. In strategic terms, the only necessary things to do are to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an adequate supply of water for irrigation in dry years (by encouraging water harvesting on farms as well as access to aquifers and res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ervoirs) and facilitate the breeding and commercialisation of stress-tolerant crop varieties, whether GM or not. If climatic changes are significant and sustained, the agricultural supply chain will also surely look at growing new crops such as sunflowers,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> currently not adapted to UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">growing conditions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Desaint N, Varbanova</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> M. The use and value of polling to determine public opinion on GMOs in Europe: Limitations and ways forward. GM Crops and Food: Biotechnology in Agriculture and the Food Chain 2013; 4:8 - 7; PMID: 24225741; http://dx.doi.org/10.4161/gmcr.26776</span></p></body></html>